Malaysia said Sunday the number of countries searching for a missing airliner had nearly doubled to 25 as a full-scale criminal probe into its disappearance got under way, with particular scrutiny of the pilots. Passengers look at a "digital earth" displayed at Kuala Lumpur International Airport (KLIA) in Sepang, outside Kuala Lumpur on March 16, 2014Transport Minister Hishammuddin Hussein said the number of participating countries had jumped from 14 to 25 as the search for the aircraft focused on two vast, and vastly contrasting, land and ocean transport corridors.  The dramatic "re-calibration" will inevitably bring "new challenges of coordination and diplomacy", the minister said. This article is older than 60 days, which we reserve for our premium members only. You can subscribe to our premium member subscription, here. 